 std::io, std::fs, std::net and std::path"}], "state": "open", "locked": false, "assignee": null, "assignees": [], "milestone": null, "comments": 2, "created_at": "2022-04-10T19:28:21Z", "updated_at": "2022-05-24T19:22:41Z", "closed_at": null, "author_association": "MEMBER", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "I found in https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/95170 that python is smarter than rust about this:\r\n> If the destination is on the current filesystem, then [os.rename()](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html#os.rename) is used. Otherwise, src is copied to dst using copy_function and then removed. In case of symlinks, a new symlink pointing to the target of src will be created in or as dst and src will be removed.\r\n\r\nhttps://docs.python.org/3/library/shutil.html\r\n\r\nIt might be nice to do the same in libstd, instead of giving a hard error when the source and destination are on different file systems.\r\n\r\n_Originally posted by @jyn514 in https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/95170#discussion_r832226965_", "closed_by": null, "reactions": {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/issues/95890/reactions", "total_count": 0, "+1": 0, "-1": 0, "laugh": 0, "hooray": 0, "confused": 0, "heart": 0, "rocket": 0, "eyes": 0}, "timeline_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/issues/95890/timeline", "performed_via_github_app": null, "state_reason": null}